Analysis of students performance in Maths course

Adity Bhargav(3814507), Anushka Sharma(3817004), Ramit Tyagi(3822900)

Data Source and Description

The dataset titled ‘Student Alcohol Consumption’ has been sourced from :

Cortez, P. and Silva, A., 2008. Using Data Mining To Predict Secondary School Student Performance. [online] Kaggle. Available at: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption [Accessed 15 September 2020].

The data was obtained from a survey that was conducted for students who are enrolled in mathematics course. The survey was performed by asking students to fill a single A4 sheet of questionnaire containing 37 questions. It contains a lot of interesting social, gender and study information about the students. The data was collected in the academic year of 2005-06 from two public schools (Gabriel Pereira and Mousinho da Silveira) from the Alentejo region of Portugal. In Portugal, a 20-point grading scale is used to measure student’s performance, where 0 is the lowest grade and 20 is a perfect score.

In this study we have taken a closer look at the survey data for the students who are enrolled in mathematics course. The dataset used for this project is an open source file named (student-mat.csv), has 395 student observations across 33 variables. Furthermore, we will be utilizing the following variables: -

Data Description
ï..NAME DATA.TYPE UNIT DESCRIPTION
school Binary Unknown Student’s school ‘GP’ - Gabriel Pereira or ‘MS’ - Mousinho da Silveira
sex Binary Unknown Student’s sex ‘F’ - female or ‘M’ - male
age Numeric Years Student’s age
address Binary Unknown Student’s home address type
Mjob Nominal Unknown Mother’s job
Fjob Nominal Unknown Father’s job
reason Nominal Unknown Reason to choose this school (close to ‘home’, school ‘reputation’, ‘course’ preference or ‘other’)
higher Binary Unknown Wants to take higher education (yes or no)
internet Binary Unknown Internet access at home (yes or no)
Dalc Numeric Unknown Workday alcohol consumption: from 1 (very low) to 5 (very high)
Walc Numeric Unknown Weekend alcohol consumption: from 1 (very low) to 5 (very high)
activities Binary Unknown Extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
G1 Numeric Unknown First period grade: from 0 to 20, output target (Related with the course subject- Math)
G2 Numeric Unknown Second period grade: from 0 to 20, output target (Related with the course subject- Math)
G3 Numeric Unknown Final grade: from 0 to 20, output target (Related with the course subject- Math)

The target feature for this data is G3 that represents the final grade(output target) of students in maths course. The grade is dependent on several factors for instance internet accessibility, study-time, alcohol consumption, etc.

Goals and Objective

The main objective of this survey data is to explore all the possible factors that affect the lifestyle and grades of students from two different schools, Gabriel Pereira and Mousinho da Silveir, who are enrolled in maths course. The aim is to contemplate the influence of several aspects on student’s life and their final grades. These factors will be explored using appropriate visualizing tools. The analysis will be conducted by examining various qualitative and quantitative factors that include gender, internet accessibility, parent’s education and occupation etc. Using exploratory data analysis with visual methods, some of the factors that are considered to have the most influence on students will be plotted. These features/aspects will be explored using visualization plots like bar graphs, pie charts, histograms and boxplots to understand their effect on student’s lifestyle and their academic performance. The results that will be generated from each plot may or may not vary from the original assumptions. The goal is to find out the major factors which actually have an impact on student’s final grades contemplating their drinking habits, their family background and all the other features/factors included in the survey data.
The final outcome of this analysis can be used by teachers and parents all around the world to understand what all conditions affect a student’s grades and lifestyle. This understanding can further help the teachers and parents to develop more efficient ways of teaching and parenting.

#Importing student-mat.csv 

student_math<- read_csv("Group14_Data.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_character(),

##   freetime = col_double(),
##   goout = col_double(),

##   health = col_double(),
##   absences = col_double(),
##   G1 = col_double(),
##   G2 = col_double(),
##   G3 = col_double()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
#Type conversions
student_math$school<- factor(student_math$school, labels = c("Gabriel Pereira", "Mousinho da Silveira"))

student_math$sex<- factor(student_math$sex, labels = c("Female", "Male"))

student_math$address<- factor(student_math$address, labels = c("Rural", "Urban"))

student_math$famsize<- factor(student_math$famsize)

student_math$Pstatus<- factor(student_math$Pstatus, labels = c("Living apart", "Living together"))

student_math$Medu<- factor(student_math$Medu, labels = c("None", "Primary Education","5th to 9th grade", "Secondary Education", "Higher Education"))

student_math$Fedu<-factor(student_math$Fedu,labels = c("None", "Primary Education","5th to 9th grade", "Secondary Education", "Higher Education"))

student_math$Mjob<- factor(student_math$Mjob)

student_math$Fjob<- factor(student_math$Fjob)

student_math$reason<- factor(student_math$reason, labels = c("Course preference", "Distance from home", "Other reasons", "School reputation"))

student_math$internet<- factor(student_math$internet, labels = c("No", "Yes"))

student_math$Walc<- factor(student_math$Walc,labels = c("Very low", "Low", "Medium", "High", "Very High"))

student_math$Dalc<- factor(student_math$Dalc, labels = c("Very low", "Low", "Medium", "High", "Very High"))

student_math$higher<- factor(student_math$higher, labels = c("No", "Yes"))

student_math$studytime<- factor(student_math$studytime,labels = c("Less than 2 hours","2-5 hours","5-10 hours","Greater than 10 hours"))

student_math$activities<- factor(student_math$activities, labels = c("No","Yes"))

#Checking for missing values

  if (is.numeric(x)) (is.infinite(x) | is.nan(x) | is.na(x))
}

#PLOT 1 - Sex Ratio in Maths course

freq1 <- as.data.frame(table(factor(student_math$sex)))
freq1Desc<- freq1[order(-freq1[-2]),]
## Warning in Ops.factor(left): '-' not meaningful for factors
sexfreq <- round(freq1Desc[,2]/sum(freq1Desc[,2])*100,2)
sexfreq <- paste(sexfreq,"%")

sex <- levels(freq1[, 1])


pie(freq1Desc[,2], labels=(sexfreq), col = c("#F46036", "#5B85AA"),
    main = "Sex ratio in Maths course",radius = 1.01, cex = .8)
legend("topright",inset = 0, bty = "n", legend=sex, col = c("#F46036", "#5B85AA"),
       pch = 15, cex = .8)

#PLOT 3 - Desire to pursue higher education

p3<- ggplot(data = student_math, aes(x= higher, fill= higher))
p3 + geom_bar() +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(..prop..), group =2), stat="count", vjust = -0.5, position = position_dodge(0.9)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#F46036", "#5B85AA")) +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Higher education plans")) +
  ggtitle(label = "Student's desire to pursue higher education") +
  labs(x= "Desire to pursue higher education", y= "Count of students") +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "gray94"),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        plot.title = element_text(color = "black", size = 12, face = "bold"))
